l |accessdate=June 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204105843/http://www.thomasnelson.com/goliath-must-fall |archive-date=February 4, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* {{cite book|author1-last=Giglio |author1-first=Louie |author1-mask=3 |title=Indescribable: 100 Devotions About God & Science |location=Nashville, TN |publisher=Thomas Nelson |date=2017 |isbn=9780718086107 |oclc=979564065 }}\n* {{cite book|author1-last=Giglio |author1-first=Louie |author1-mask=3 |title=Not Forsaken: Finding Freedom as Sons & Daughters of a Perfect Father |location=Nashville, TN |publisher=B&H Books |date=2019 |isbn=9781535956956 |oclc=1081385221 }}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bhpublishinggroup.com/bestselling-author-and-passion-founder-louie-giglio-releases-new-book-not-forsaken-more-passion-resources-to-come-this-year/|title=Bestselling author and Passion founder Louie Giglio Releases new book \"Not Forsaken,\" More Passion resources to come this year|date=2019-02-05|website=B&H Publishing|language=en|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|author1-last=Giglio |author1-first=Louie |author1-mask=3 |title=How Great Is Our God: 100 Indescribable Devotions About God and Science |location=Nashville, TN |publisher=Tommy Nelson |date=2019 |isbn=9781400217212 |oclc=1104859319 }}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianpost.com/books/louie-giglios-new-childrens-devotional-hopes-to-bridge-the-divide-between-god-and-science.html|title=Louie Giglio's new children's devotional hopes to bridge the divide between God and science|date=2019-12-09|website=Christian Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.passioncitychurch.com Passion City Church]\n* [http://www.268generation.com 268generation] - Web site for Passion Conferences\n* [http://www.sixstepsrecords.com sixstepsrecords] - Home of Crowder, Sean Curran, Kristian Stanfill, and Passion.\n* [https://www.louiegiglio.com/ louiegiglio.com] - Louie Giglio official website\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Giglio, Louie}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Protestant ministers and clergy]]\n[[Category:Christian writers]]\n[[Category:Baylor University alumni]]\n[[Category:Southern Baptists]]\n[[Category:Georgia State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary alumni]]\n[[Category:Grace Theological Seminary alumni]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louie_Giglio"}
{"title_page": "Gnomon (novel)", "text_new": "{{book-stub}}\n\n\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Gnomon\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = \n| image_caption = \n| author        = Nick Harkaway\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| subject       = <!-- Subject is not relevant for fiction -->\n| genre         = [[Science fiction]]\n| published     = 2017\n| media_type    = Print\n| pages         = 704\n| isbn          = 978-1-473-53954-9\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n| wikisource    = \n}}\n\n\n'''''Gnomon''''' is a [[science fiction]] novel by [[Nick Harkaway]]. The book  deals with a state that exerts ubiquitous surveillance on its population. A detective investigates a murder through unconventional methods that leads to questions about her society's very nature.\n\n== Plot summary ==\n\nIn a near future [[United Kingdom]], now governed by continuous [[direct democracy]], all of Britain is under constant surveillance by the nigh-omniscient AI called \"The System.\" Witness inspector Mielikki Neith it tasked with investigating the death of [[refusenik]] Diana Hunter's death following her forced interrogation\u2014where Hunter's memories were extracted\u2014while in custody. Neith quickly finds that Hunter's memories are a maze of other lives and narratives and must discover what this means for the continued operation of the System.\n\n==Reception==\nIn [[The Independent|''The Independent'']], Darragh McManus gave a negative review,<ref>{{cite web |last1=McManus |first1=Darragh |title=Baffling utopian epic ladled with elegant nonsense |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/books/book-reviews/baffling-utopian-epic-ladled-with-elegant-nonsense-36305841.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> calling the book a \"baffling utopian epic ladled with elegant nonsense.\" While praising Harkaway for \"writing women extremely well\" (\"Hunter, Neith and Athenais are the book's most vivid creations and strongest elements\"), and saying \"there are a lot of things to enjoy in ''Gnomon'',\" she nevertheless felt it was \"hugely confusing.\"\n\n<blockquote>It's not the length, though the novel is much too long. It's not that Harkaway has a tendency to overwrite: both in labouring a point or observation before labouring it some more, and using arcane (and possibly non-existent) words where a normal, widely-known one was available. [...] My main problem is that Gnomon doesn't make a lick of sense. Or maybe it does, in the author's mind, but I'm afraid I was baffled, to the point of paralysed stupidity. I genuinely couldn't tell you, by the end, who did what and when, whether anything reported here actually occurred, whether any or all of these characters even exist.</blockquote>\n\nIn [[The Guardian|''The Guardian'']], Steven Poole also gave the book a negative review.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Poole |first1=Steven |title=Gnomon by Nick Harkaway review \u2013 a future of total surveillance |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/nov/16/gnomon-nick-harkaway-review-science-fiction-artifical-intelligence |website=The Guardian |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \"Gnomon [...] reads like the first draft of what might have been a tighter 400-page book rather than a rambling 700-pager. Progress is routinely halted by sketchy Wikipedia-style exposition-dumps about tidal flow or [[behavioural economics]], or a character asking herself a whole page or two of questions about what just happened, or vague disquisitions on the meaning of identity. Things are repeatedly explained, unnecessarily.\" Still, Poole also said, \"Such defects wouldn\u2019t be so annoying were it not obvious that Nick Harkaway can sometimes be a very good writer indeed. Readers who are prepared to mentally edit the book as they go along, as the author and editor have not, will encounter a host of highly enjoyable fragments and suggestive ideas.\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33852053-gnomon ''Gnomon'' on Goodreads]\n\n[[Category:2017 novels]]\n[[Category:British novels]]\n[[Category:Science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:English-language novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{book-stub}}\n\n\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Gnomon\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = \n| image_caption = \n| author        = Nick Harkaway\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| subject       = <!-- Subject is not relevant for fiction -->\n| genre         = [[Science fiction]]\n| published     = 2017\n| media_type    = Print\n| pages         = 704\n| isbn          = 978-1-473-53954-9\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n| wikisource    = \n}}\n\n\n'''''Gnomon''''' is a [[science fiction]] novel by [[Nick Harkaway]]. The book  deals with a state that exerts ubiquitous surveillance on its population. A detective investigates a murder through unconventional methods that leads to questions about her society's very nature.\n\n== Plot summary ==\n\nIn a near future [[United Kingdom]], all of Britain, now governed by continuous [[direct democracy]], is under constant surveillance by the nigh-omniscient AI called \"The System.\" Witness inspector Mielikki Neith it tasked with investigating the death of [[refusenik]] Diana Hunter's death following her forced interrogation\u2014where Hunter's memories were extracted\u2014while in custody. Neith quickly finds that Hunter's memories are a maze of other lives and narratives and must discover what this means for the continued operation of the System.\n\n==Reception==\nIn [[The Independent|''The Independent'']], Darragh McManus gave a negative review,<ref>{{cite web |last1=McManus |first1=Darragh |title=Baffling utopian epic ladled with elegant nonsense |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/books/book-reviews/baffling-utopian-epic-ladled-with-elegant-nonsense-36305841.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> calling the book a \"baffling utopian epic ladled with elegant nonsense.\" While praising Harkaway for \"writing women extremely well\" (\"Hunter, Neith and Athenais are the book's most vivid creations and strongest elements\"), and saying \"there are a lot of things to enjoy in ''Gnomon'',\" she nevertheless felt it was \"hugely confusing.\"\n\n<blockquote>It's not the length, though the novel is much too long. It's not that Harkaway has a tendency to overwrite: both in labouring a point or observation before labouring it some more, and using arcane (and possibly non-existent) words where a normal, widely-known one was available. [...] My main problem is that Gnomon doesn't make a lick of sense. Or maybe it does, in the author's mind, but I'm afraid I was baffled, to the point of paralysed stupidity. I genuinely couldn't tell you, by the end, who did what and when, whether anything reported here actually occurred, whether any or all of these characters even exist.</blockquote>\n\nIn [[The Guardian|''The Guardian'']], Steven Poole also gave the book a negative review.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Poole |first1=Steven |title=Gnomon by Nick Harkaway review \u2013 a future of total surveillance |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/nov/16/gnomon-nick-harkaway-review-science-fiction-artifical-intelligence |website=The Guardian |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \"Gnomon [...] reads like the first draft of what might have been a tighter 400-page book rather than a rambling 700-pager. Progress is routinely halted by sketchy Wikipedia-style exposition-dumps about tidal flow or [[behavioural economics]], or a character asking herself a whole page or two of questions about what just happened, or vague disquisitions on the meaning of identity. Things are repeatedly explained, unnecessarily.\" Still, Poole also said, \"Such defects wouldn\u2019t be so annoying were it not obvious that Nick Harkaway can sometimes be a very good writer indeed. Readers who are prepared to mentally edit the book as they go along, as the author and editor have not, will encounter a host of highly enjoyable fragments and suggestive ideas.\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33852053-gnomon ''Gnomon'' on Goodreads]\n\n[[Category:2017 novels]]\n[[Category:British novels]]\n[[Category:Science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:English-language novels]]\n", "name_user": "RobertM525", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot summary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gnomon_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Lou Cordileone", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Lou Cordileone\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| currentteam         = \n| number              = 51, 74, 79\n| position            = [[Guard (American football)|Guard]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1937|8|4|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 1\n| weight_lbs          = 250\n| high_school         = [[St. Michael's High School (Union City, New Jersey)|Union City (NJ) St. Michael's]]\n| college             = [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]]\n| draftyear           = 1960\n| draftround          = 1\n| draftpick           = 12\n| afldraftyear        = 1960\n| afldraftround       = 1\n| afldraftpick        = First Selections\n| pastteams           = \n* [[New York Giants]] (1960)\n* [[San Francisco 49ers]] (1961)\n* [[Los Angeles Rams (1946\u201394)|Los Angeles Rams]] (1962)\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (1962\u20131966)\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] (1967\u20131968)\n| highlights          = \n| nflnew              = loucordileone/2511990\n| pfr                 = CordLo20\n}}\n\n'''Louis Anthony Cordileone''' (born August 4, 1937) is a former [[American football]] [[offensive lineman]], primarily [[Guard (American football)|guard]], who in nine years played six seasons<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.canalstreetchronicles.com/2017/6/24/15860056/countdown-to-new-orleans-saints-kickoff-history-of-no-79-lou-cordileone-emanuel-zanders-bryce-harris|title=Countdown to Saints Kickoff: A History of No. 79|work=Canal Street Chronicles|access-date=September 2, 2018}}</ref> in the [[National Football League]], for five different teams. He played [[college football]] at [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]] and was [[1960_NFL_Draft#Round_one|drafted in the first round (twelfth overall)]] of the [[1960 NFL Draft]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}. \n\nCordileone is best-known for being traded in 1961 from the [[New York Giants]] to the [[San Francisco 49ers]] for quarterback [[Y. A. Tittle]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/y-a-tittle-nfl-legend-and-pro-football-hall-of-famer-passes-away-at-age-90/|title=Y.A. Tittle, NFL legend and Pro Football Hall of Famer, dies at age 90|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=September 2, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/123238/2017/10/10/y-a-tittle-was-the-very-portrait-of-a-certain-time-and-place-in-the-brutal-enduring-sport-of-football/|title=Y.A. Tittle was the very portrait of a certain time and...|last=Spander|first=Art|work=The Athletic|access-date=September 2, 2018}}</ref> At the time, Tittle was 34 years old and a 4-time Pro Bowler. Cordileone was quoted as reacting \"Me, even up for Y. A. Tittle? You're kidding\"<ref name=SI1996>{{cite journal|last1=Fimrite|first1=Ron|title=49ers Quarterback Y. A. Tittle November 22, 1954|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=September 2, 1996|volume=35|issue=10|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1996/09/02/217050/49ers-quarterback-ya-tittle-november-22-1954|accessdate=August 14, 2016}}</ref>, and later remarked that the Giants traded him for \"a 42-year-old quarterback\".<ref name=Bridget>{{cite news|last1=Wentworth|first1=Bridget|title=Tittle didn't want Giants trade|url=http://www.nj.com/sports/ledger/dorfman/index.ssf/2009/09/tittle_didnt_want_giants_trade.html|accessdate=August 17, 2016|work=The Star-Ledger|date=September 22, 2009}}</ref> \n\nHis stay in San Francisco was short lived, as he went to the Rams in 1962, where he played only 2 games, before moving to Pittsburgh, playing 26 games until the end of the 1963 season. After a 3 year hiatus, he joined the expansion team New Orleans Saints for their first two seasons, 1967 and 1968, as offensive guard and defensive tackle. In his last season, he fumbled once, and returned an interception for 7 yards, after having recovered three fumbles in his first two pro seasons.\n\nIn 2013 Cordileone starred in the [[TV Land]] reality show ''[[Forever Young (TV series)|Forever Young]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvland.com/shows/forever-young |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 17, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218042049/http://www.tvland.com/shows/forever-young |archivedate=February 18, 2013 }} </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1960 NFL Draft}}\n{{GiantsFirstPick}}\n{{1967 New Orleans Saints}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cordileone, Lou}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football offensive linemen]]\n[[Category:Clemson Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:New York Giants players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers players]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Jersey]]\n\n\n{{offensive-lineman-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Lou Cordileone\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| currentteam         = \n| number              = 51, 74, 79\n| position            = [[Guard (American football)|Guard]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1937|8|4|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 1\n| weight_lbs          = 250\n| high_school         = [[St. Michael's High School (Union City, New Jersey)|Union City (NJ) St. Michael's]]\n| college             = [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]]\n| draftyear           = 1960\n| draftround          = 1\n| draftpick           = 12\n| afldraftyear        = 1960\n| afldraftround       = 1\n| afldraftpick        = First Selections\n| pastteams           = \n* [[New York Giants]] (1960)\n* [[San Francisco 49ers]] (1961)\n* [[Los Angeles Rams (1946\u201394)|Los Angeles Rams]] (1962)\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (1962\u20131966)\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] (1967\u20131968)\n| highlights          = \n| nflnew              = loucordileone/2511990\n| pfr                 = CordLo20\n}}\n\n'''Louis Anthony Cordileone''' (born August 4, 1937) is a former [[American football]] [[offensive lineman]], primarily [[Guard (American football)|guard]], who in nine years played six seasons<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.canalstreetchronicles.com/2017/6/24/15860056/countdown-to-new-orleans-saints-kickoff-history-of-no-79-lou-cordileone-emanuel-zanders-bryce-harris|title=Countdown to Saints Kickoff: A History of No. 79|work=Canal Street Chronicles|access-date=September 2, 2018}}</ref> in the [[National Football League]], for five different teams. He played [[college football]] at [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]] and was [[1960_NFL_Draft#Round_one|drafted in the first round (twelfth overall)]] of the [[1960 NFL Draft]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}. \n\nCordileone is best-known for being traded in 1961 from the [[New York Giants]] to the [[San Francisco 49ers]] for quarterback [[Y. A. Tittle]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/y-a-tittle-nfl-legend-and-pro-football-hall-of-famer-passes-away-at-age-90/|title=Y.A. Tittle, NFL legend and Pro Football Hall of Famer, dies at age 90|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=September 2, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/123238/2017/10/10/y-a-tittle-was-the-very-portrait-of-a-certain-time-and-place-in-the-brutal-enduring-sport-of-football/|title=Y.A. Tittle was the very portrait of a certain time and...|last=Spander|first=Art|work=The Athletic|access-date=September 2, 2018}}</ref> At the time, Tittle was 34 years old and a 4-time Pro Bowler. Cordileone was quoted as reacting \"Me, even up for Y. A. Tittle? You're kidding\"<ref name=SI1996>{{cite journal|last1=Fimrite|first1=Ron|title=49ers Quarterback Y. A. Tittle November 22, 1954|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=September 2, 1996|volume=35|issue=10|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1996/09/02/217050/49ers-quarterback-ya-tittle-november-22-1954|accessdate=August 14, 2016}}</ref>, and later remarked that the Giants traded him for \"a 42-year-old quarterback\"<ref name=Bridget>{{cite news|last1=Wentworth|first1=Bridget|title=Tittle didn't want Giants trade|url=http://www.nj.com/sports/ledger/dorfman/index.ssf/2009/09/tittle_didnt_want_giants_trade.html|accessdate=August 17, 2016|work=The Star-Ledger|date=September 22, 2009}}</ref>. \n\nHis stay in San Francisco was short lived, as he went to the Rams in 1962, where he played only 2 games, before moving to Pittsburgh, playing 26 games until the end of the 1963 season. After a 3 year hiatus, he joined the expansion team New Orleans Saints for their first two seasons, 1967 and 1968, as offensive guard and defensive tackle. In his last season, he fumbled once, and returned an interception for 7 yards, after having recovered three fumbles in his first two pro seasons.\n\nIn 2013 Cordileone starred in the [[TV Land]] reality show ''[[Forever Young (TV series)|Forever Young]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvland.com/shows/forever-young |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 17, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218042049/http://www.tvland.com/shows/forever-young |archivedate=February 18, 2013 }} </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1960 NFL Draft}}\n{{GiantsFirstPick}}\n{{1967 New Orleans Saints}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cordileone, Lou}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football offensive linemen]]\n[[Category:Clemson Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:New York Giants players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers players]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Jersey]]\n\n\n{{offensive-lineman-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lou_Cordileone"}
{"title_page": "Lorenzo di Credi", "text_new": "[[File:Lorenzo di Credi by Perugino.jpg|thumbnail|Lorenzo di Credi by Perugino]]\n'''Lorenzo di Credi''' (c. 1459 &ndash; January 12, 1537) was an [[Italy|Italian]] [[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]] [[Painting|painter]] and [[sculpture|sculptor]], known for his paintings on religious subjects. He first influenced [[Leonardo da Vinci]] and then in turn was greatly influenced by him.\n\n==Life==\n\n[[File:Lorenzo di Credi woman Metropolitan.jpg|thumbnail| ''Portrait of a Young Woman''. ]]\nBorn in [[Florence]], son of goldsmith Andrea di Oderigo Barducci, he had started work in [[Andrea del Verrocchio]]'s workshop by 1480.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Regoli|first=G. Dalli|date=13 December 2017|title=Lorenzo di Credi|url=https://www.oxfordartonline.com/view/10.1093/benz/9780199773787.001.0001/acref-9780199773787-e-00044226|journal=|language=en|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1093/benz/9780199773787.001.0001/acref-9780199773787-e-00044226|via=Oxford Art Online|doi-broken-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> After the death of his master, he inherited the direction of the workshop. For [[Pistoia Cathedral]] he completed the painting of the ''Madonna Enthroned between John the Baptist and St. Donatus'' which had been partially painted by his master, Verrocchio, but was left unfinished when Verrocchio went to Venice.\n\nAmongst his other early works are an ''Annunciation'' in the [[Uffizi]], a ''Madonna with Child'' in the [[Galleria Sabauda]] of [[Turin]], and ''Adoration of the Child'' in the Querini Stampalia of [[Venice]]. Of a later period are a ''Madonna and Saints'' (1493; [[Mus\u00e9e du Louvre|Mus\u00e9e du Louvre, Paris]]) and an ''Adoration of the Child'' in the [[Uffizi]]. In [[Fiesole]], he remade parts of [[Fra Angelico]]'s panels on the altars of the church of [[Convent of San Domenico, Fiesole|San Domenico]].\n\nLorenzo's mature works (such as the ''Crucifixion'' in the [[G\u00f6ttingen City Museum]], the ''[[Adoration of the Shepherds (Lorenzo di Credi)|Adoration of the Shepherds]]'' of the [[Uffizi Gallery|Uffizi]], the ''Annunciation'' in [[Cambridge]] and the ''Madonna and Saints'' of [[Pistoia]]) are influenced by [[Fra Bartolomeo]], [[Perugino]] and the young [[Raphael]]. \n\nIn recent times, one of di Credi's works gained attention when scholars pointed out a resemblance between the face of [[Mona Lisa]] by [[Leonardo da Vinci]] and the face of [[Caterina Sforza]] in a portrait by him. Caterina Sforza was the Lady of [[Forl\u00ec]] and [[Imola]] in [[Romagna]], later prisoner of [[Cesare Borgia]]. The portrait, known also as ''La dama dei gelsomini'', is now in the Pinacoteca of Forl\u00ec.\n<gallery mode=packed heights=\"133px\" > \nCaterina Sforza incut.jpg|Caterina Sforza\nLorenzo di Credi - Madonna Dreyfus.jpg| ''Dreyfus Madonna''\nPinacoteca Querini Stampalia - Madonna e San Giovannino adoranti il Bambino - Lorenzo di Credi.jpg|Our Lady and the young St John the Baptist adoring the Child\nLorenzo di Credi - Madonna Adoring the Child - Tondo Karlsruhe.jpg|Madonna Adoring the Child|\nLorenco di Credi-Adoration.jpg| ''Adoration'', [[National Museum of Serbia]], [[Belgrade]]\nLorenzo di credi (bottega) e pittore nordico, madonna col bambino e santi, 1500-10 ca., da s. pietro al terreno a brollo 02.JPG|\nAjaccio Di Credi St Francois.JPG|St Francis\n</gallery>\n\n\n<!-- <gallery mode=packed heights=\"133px\" > \nFile:Beato angelico, pala fiesole, 1424-1425.jpg \n\n\nFile:Lorenzocredi.jpg\n</gallery> -->\n\n==See also==\n* [[Giovanni Cianfanini]]\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book| first= James R.|last= Hobbes| year= 1849|title=Picture collector's manual; Dictionary of Painters (volume II)|  editor =   |publisher= T. & W. Boone, 29 Bond Street, London; Digitized by Googlebooks (2006) from Oxford library| id= |url= https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_4koEAAAAQAAJ| page= [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_4koEAAAAQAAJ/page/n179 153]}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/90258/rec/1 ''Leonardo da Vinci, Master Draftsman''], exhibition catalog fully online as PDF from The Metropolitan Museum of Art Library, which contains material on Lorenzo di Credi (see index)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lorenzo di Credi}}\n[[Category:1450s births]]\n[[Category:1537 deaths]]\n[[Category:Florentine painters]]\n[[Category:15th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:Italian male painters]]\n[[Category:16th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:Renaissance painters]]\n[[Category:Italian goldsmiths]]\n[[Category:15th-century Italian sculptors]]\n[[Category:Italian male sculptors]]\n[[Category:16th-century Italian sculptors]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Lorenzo di Credi by Perugino.jpg|thumbnail|Lorenzo di Credi by Perugino]]\n'''Lorenzo di Credi''' (c. 1459 &ndash; January 12, 1537) was an [[Italy|Italian]] [[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]] [[Painting|painter]] and [[sculpture|sculptor]], known for his paintings on religious subjects. He first influenced [[Leonardo da Vinci]] and then in turn was greatly influenced by him.\n\n==Life==\n\n[[File:Lorenzo di Credi woman Metropolitan.jpg|thumbnail| ''Portrait of a Young Woman''. ]]\nBorn in [[Florence]], son of goldsmith Andrea di Oderigo Barducci, he had started work in [[Andrea del Verrocchio]]'s workshop by 1480<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Regoli|first=G. Dalli|date=13 December 2017|title=Lorenzo di Credi|url=https://www.oxfordartonline.com/view/10.1093/benz/9780199773787.001.0001/acref-9780199773787-e-00044226|journal=|language=en|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1093/benz/9780199773787.001.0001/acref-9780199773787-e-00044226|via=Oxford Art Online|doi-broken-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>. After the death of his master, he inherited the direction of the workshop. For [[Pistoia Cathedral]] he completed the painting of the ''Madonna Enthroned between John the Baptist and St. Donatus'' which had been partially painted by his master, Verrocchio, but was left unfinished when Verrocchio went to Venice.\n\nAmongst his other early works are an ''Annunciation'' in the [[Uffizi]], a ''Madonna with Child'' in the [[Galleria Sabauda]] of [[Turin]], and ''Adoration of the Child'' in the Querini Stampalia of [[Venice]]. Of a later period are a ''Madonna and Saints'' (1493; [[Mus\u00e9e du Louvre|Mus\u00e9e du Louvre, Paris]]) and an ''Adoration of the Child'' in the [[Uffizi]]. In [[Fiesole]], he remade parts of [[Fra Angelico]]'s panels on the altars of the church of [[Convent of San Domenico, Fiesole|San Domenico]].\n\nLorenzo's mature works (such as the ''Crucifixion'' in the [[G\u00f6ttingen City Museum]], the ''[[Adoration of the Shepherds (Lorenzo di Credi)|Adoration of the Shepherds]]'' of the [[Uffizi Gallery|Uffizi]], the ''Annunciation'' in [[Cambridge]] and the ''Madonna and Saints'' of [[Pistoia]]) are influenced by [[Fra Bartolomeo]], [[Perugino]] and the young [[Raphael]]. \n\nIn recent times, one of di Credi's works gained attention when scholars pointed out a resemblance between the face of [[Mona Lisa]] by [[Leonardo da Vinci]] and the face of [[Caterina Sforza]] in a portrait by him. Caterina Sforza was the Lady of [[Forl\u00ec]] and [[Imola]] in [[Romagna]], later prisoner of [[Cesare Borgia]]. The portrait, known also as ''La dama dei gelsomini'', is now in the Pinacoteca of Forl\u00ec.\n<gallery mode=packed heights=\"133px\" > \nCaterina Sforza incut.jpg|Caterina Sforza\nLorenzo di Credi - Madonna Dreyfus.jpg| ''Dreyfus Madonna''\nPinacoteca Querini Stampalia - Madonna e San Giovannino adoranti il Bambino - Lorenzo di Credi.jpg|Our Lady and the young St John the Baptist adoring the Child\nLorenzo di Credi - Madonna Adoring the Child - Tondo Karlsruhe.jpg|Madonna Adoring the Child|\nLorenco di Credi-Adoration.jpg| ''Adoration'', [[National Museum of Serbia]], [[Belgrade]]\nLorenzo di credi (bottega) e pittore nordico, madonna col bambino e santi, 1500-10 ca., da s. pietro al terreno a brollo 02.JPG|\nAjaccio Di Credi St Francois.JPG|St Francis\n</gallery>\n\n\n<!-- <gallery mode=packed heights=\"133px\" > \nFile:Beato angelico, pala fiesole, 1424-1425.jpg \n\n\nFile:Lorenzocredi.jpg\n</gallery> -->\n\n==See also==\n* [[Giovanni Cianfanini]]\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book| first= James R.|last= Hobbes| year= 1849|title=Picture collector's manual; Dictionary of Painters (volume II)|  editor =   |publisher= T. & W. Boone, 29 Bond Street, London; Digitized by Googlebooks (2006) from Oxford library| id= |url= https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_4koEAAAAQAAJ| page= [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_4koEAAAAQAAJ/page/n179 153]}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/90258/rec/1 ''Leonardo da Vinci, Master Draftsman''], exhibition catalog fully online as PDF from The Metropolitan Museum of Art Library, which contains material on Lorenzo di Credi (see index)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lorenzo di Credi}}\n[[Category:1450s births]]\n[[Category:1537 deaths]]\n[[Category:Florentine painters]]\n[[Category:15th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:Italian male painters]]\n[[Category:16th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:Renaissance painters]]\n[[Category:Italian goldsmiths]]\n[[Category:15th-century Italian sculptors]]\n[[Category:Italian male sculptors]]\n[[Category:16th-century Italian sculptors]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorenzo_di_Credi"}
{"title_page": "Longbenton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2009}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n|country = England      \n|official_name = Longbenton\n|static_image_name = Quorum Business Park, redboxdesign, Critical Tortoise.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Quorum Business Park situated in North of Longbenton\n|coordinates = {{coord|55.00|-1.57|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference=     NZ2668\n| population = 10,617\n| population_ref = (2011 Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13689628&c=NE12+7ES&d=14&e=62&g=6359188&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1435935936502&enc=1|title=North Tyneside ward population 2011|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>\n|metropolitan_borough=          [[North Tyneside]]\n|region=                  North East England\n|metropolitan_county =            [[Tyne and Wear]]\n|constituency_westminster=     [[North Tyneside (UK Parliament constituency)|North Tyneside]] \n|post_town=        NEWCASTLE UPON TYNE\n|postcode_district =       NE12\n|postcode_area=            NE   \n|dial_code=      0191\n}}\n\n'''Longbenton''' is a district of [[North Tyneside]], [[England]]. It is largely occupied by an extensive estate originally built as municipal housing by Newcastle City Council in the 1950s and 1960s. It is served by the [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] stations [[Longbenton Metro station]] and [[Four Lane Ends Metro Station]]. Nearby places are [[Killingworth]], [[Forest Hall]], Four Lane Ends, [[West Moor]], [[Heaton, Newcastle|Heaton]] and South [[Gosforth]], in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]. The Longbenton and Killingworth Urban Area had a population of 34,878 in 2001.<ref>[http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/Expodata/Spreadsheets/D8271.xls Office for National Statistics : ''Census 2001 : Urban Areas : Table KS01 : Usual Resident Population''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208210730/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/Expodata/Spreadsheets/D8271.xls |date=2007-02-08 }} Retrieved 2009-08-26</ref> This figure increased to 37,070 in 2011.<ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1119883721</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nTwo secondary schools are located in the township, [[Longbenton Community College]] and [[St Mary's Catholic Comprehensive School]], along with four primary schools. The four primary schools are Benton Dene Primary School,<ref>http://www.bentondeneschools.org.uk/</ref> Balliol Primary School, St Bartholomew's, and St. Stephen's Primary School.\nNurseries offering childcare in Longbenton include Leigh's Nurseries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leighsnurseries.co.uk/|title=Leigh's Nurseries|website=Leigh's Nurseries|url-status=live|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLongbenton Football Club are an FA-affiliated team and as of 2012/13 season play in the Northern Alliance Division 2. [http://www.longbentonfc.co.uk/ Longbenton Football Club]. Their home ground is situated behind the Oxford Centre.\n\n==Demography==\nLongbenton had a population of 10,617 in 2011. The figure is given as a ward because the Longbenton Urban Subdivision also encompasses its larger neighbour, [[Killingworth]] as well as parts of neighbouring areas.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ethnic Groups 2011 !! Longbenton ward !! [[Metropolitan Borough of North Tyneside]]\n|-\n| White British || 92.6% || 95.1%\n|-\n| Asian || 3.5% || 1.9%\n|-\n| Black || 0.7% || 0.4%\n|}\n\n<ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1237320784</ref><ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1946157066</ref>\n\nPossibly due to the fact it borders Newcastle, Longbenton is one of the most ethnically diverse areas in North Tyneside.\n\n== Churches ==\nLongbenton is served by [https://web.archive.org/web/20091216202817/http://www.achurchnearyou.com/long-benton-st-mary-magdalene/ St. Mary Magdalene] (Church of England) on West Farm Ave, [http://longbenton-methodist.moonfruit.com the Methodist church] at one end of Chesters Ave and [http://www.thekingscastlechurch.org.uk The King's Castle] (independent) at the other end of Chesters Ave.\n\nThe [[parish church]] is [[St Bartholomew's Church, Long Benton]].\n\n== Business ==\nLongbenton is the site of [[BT Group|BT]]'s Newcastle call centre. Balliol Business Park is located in Longbenton where a [[Greggs]] production site and, until recently, two large [[Sitel]] call centres were located.<ref>http://www.thejournal.co.uk/business/business-news/jobs-boost-sitel-new-office-4420727</ref> The UK production site for the [[Findus]] frozen food brand was based in Longbenton until mid-January 2009 when, through cost-cutting and fire damage, the factory was closed, with the loss of around 400 jobs.  Following the award of a grant from Regional development agency One North East the factory was repaired and reopened as Longbenton Foods in 2010.<ref>http://www.newsguardian.co.uk/news/findus-factory-refurbishment-will-create-more-than-300-jobs-1-1599651</ref> Countrystyle foods took over the site in 2012 and now has roughly 200 staff working there.\n\n== Notable residents ==\nFootballer [[Peter Beardsley]] grew up in Longbenton and attended [[Longbenton High School]].<ref>http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/six-interesting-facts-about-longbenton-1342144</ref>\n\n[[Thomas Addison]], 19th-century physician and scientist and discoverer of, among others, [[Addison's disease]] and [[Pernicious anaemia]] was born and educated in Longbenton.<ref>http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/six-interesting-facts-about-longbenton-1342144</ref> He is widely regarded as one of the leading lights of 19th-century medicine, and was famous for his brilliant lecturing style, compassion and empathy for patients (not common among doctors at the time) and devotion to furthering medical science. He has a bust in his old place of work, [[Guy's Hospital]], London, and a window in his memory in St Bartholomew's parish church.\n\nWriter and poet [[Michael Roberts (writer)|Michael Roberts]] lived nearby in [[Jesmond]] in the 1930s, and he included Longbenton in his poem ''Hymn to the Sun''.<ref>[http://www.sclews.me.uk/m-roberts.html Myers Literary Guide: The North-East - MICHAEL (WILLIAM EDWARD) ROBERTS (1902 - 1948)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213103256/http://www.sclews.me.uk/m-roberts.html |date=2014-12-13 }}</ref>\n\n== Government agencies ==\n[[HM Revenue & Customs]] and [[Department for Work and Pensions]] share a major base on the Longbenton/[[City of Newcastle upon Tyne]] border, known as [[Benton Park View]]. The site employs around 7,500 workers and is a significant employment source in the area.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.longbentonfc.co.uk/ Longbenton F.C] The Official Website for Longbenton Football Club.\n* [http://www.longbentonfc.co.uk/about Longbenton F.C] About Longbenton F.C - The Story Behind the Club.\n\n{{T&W places}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan Borough of North Tyneside]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2009}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n|country = England      \n|official_name = Longbenton\n|static_image_name = Quorum Business Park, redboxdesign, Critical Tortoise.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Quorum Business Park situated in North of Longbenton\n|coordinates = {{coord|55.00|-1.57|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference=     NZ2668\n| population = 10,617\n| population_ref = (2011 Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13689628&c=NE12+7ES&d=14&e=62&g=6359188&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1435935936502&enc=1|title=North Tyneside ward population 2011|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>\n|metropolitan_borough=          [[North Tyneside]]\n|region=                  North East England\n|metropolitan_county =            [[Tyne and Wear]]\n|constituency_westminster=     [[North Tyneside (UK Parliament constituency)|North Tyneside]] \n|post_town=        NEWCASTLE UPON TYNE\n|postcode_district =       NE12\n|postcode_area=            NE   \n|dial_code=      0191\n}}\n\n'''Longbenton''' is a district of [[North Tyneside]], [[England]]. It is largely occupied by an extensive estate originally built as municipal housing by Newcastle City Council in the 1950s and 1960s. It is served by the [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] stations [[Longbenton Metro station]] and [[Four Lane Ends Metro Station]]. Nearby places are [[Killingworth]], [[Forest Hall]], Four Lane Ends, [[West Moor]], [[Heaton, Newcastle|Heaton]] and South [[Gosforth]], in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]. The Longbenton and Killingworth Urban Area had a population of 34,878 in 2001.<ref>[http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/Expodata/Spreadsheets/D8271.xls Office for National Statistics : ''Census 2001 : Urban Areas : Table KS01 : Usual Resident Population''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208210730/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/Expodata/Spreadsheets/D8271.xls |date=2007-02-08 }} Retrieved 2009-08-26</ref> This figure increased to 37,070 in 2011.<ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1119883721</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nTwo secondary schools are located in the township, [[Longbenton Community College]] and [[St Mary's Catholic Comprehensive School]], along with four primary schools. The four primary schools are Benton Dene Primary School,<ref>http://www.bentondeneschools.org.uk/</ref> Balliol Primary School, St Bartholomew's, and St. Stephen's Primary School.\nNurseries offering childcare in Longbenton include Leigh's Nurseries<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leighsnurseries.co.uk/|title=Leigh's Nurseries|website=Leigh's Nurseries|url-status=live|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>.\n\nLongbenton Football Club are an FA-affiliated team and as of 2012/13 season play in the Northern Alliance Division 2. [http://www.longbentonfc.co.uk/ Longbenton Football Club]. Their home ground is situated behind the Oxford Centre.\n\n==Demography==\nLongbenton had a population of 10,617 in 2011. The figure is given as a ward because the Longbenton Urban Subdivision also encompasses its larger neighbour, [[Killingworth]] as well as parts of neighbouring areas.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ethnic Groups 2011 !! Longbenton ward !! [[Metropolitan Borough of North Tyneside]]\n|-\n| White British || 92.6% || 95.1%\n|-\n| Asian || 3.5% || 1.9%\n|-\n| Black || 0.7% || 0.4%\n|}\n\n<ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1237320784</ref><ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/sources/census_2011_ks/report?compare=1946157066</ref>\n\nPossibly due to the fact it borders Newcastle, Longbenton is one of the most ethnically diverse areas in North Tyneside.\n\n== Churches ==\nLongbenton is served by [https://web.archive.org/web/20091216202817/http://www.achurchnearyou.com/long-benton-st-mary-magdalene/ St. Mary Magdalene] (Church of England) on West Farm Ave, [http://longbenton-methodist.moonfruit.com the Methodist church] at one end of Chesters Ave and [http://www.thekingscastlechurch.org.uk The King's Castle] (independent) at the other end of Chesters Ave.\n\nThe [[parish church]] is [[St Bartholomew's Church, Long Benton]].\n\n== Business ==\nLongbenton is the site of [[BT Group|BT]]'s Newcastle call centre. Balliol Business Park is located in Longbenton where a [[Greggs]] production site and, until recently, two large [[Sitel]] call centres were located.<ref>http://www.thejournal.co.uk/business/business-news/jobs-boost-sitel-new-office-4420727</ref> The UK production site for the [[Findus]] frozen food brand was based in Longbenton until mid-January 2009 when, through cost-cutting and fire damage, the factory was closed, with the loss of around 400 jobs.  Following the award of a grant from Regional development agency One North East the factory was repaired and reopened as Longbenton Foods in 2010.<ref>http://www.newsguardian.co.uk/news/findus-factory-refurbishment-will-create-more-than-300-jobs-1-1599651</ref> Countrystyle foods took over the site in 2012 and now has roughly 200 staff working there.\n\n== Notable residents ==\nFootballer [[Peter Beardsley]] grew up in Longbenton and attended [[Longbenton High School]].<ref>http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/six-interesting-facts-about-longbenton-1342144</ref>\n\n[[Thomas Addison]], 19th-century physician and scientist and discoverer of, among others, [[Addison's disease]] and [[Pernicious anaemia]] was born and educated in Longbenton.<ref>http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/six-interesting-facts-about-longbenton-1342144</ref> He is widely regarded as one of the leading lights of 19th-century medicine, and was famous for his brilliant lecturing style, compassion and empathy for patients (not common among doctors at the time) and devotion to furthering medical science. He has a bust in his old place of work, [[Guy's Hospital]], London, and a window in his memory in St Bartholomew's parish church.\n\nWriter and poet [[Michael Roberts (writer)|Michael Roberts]] lived nearby in [[Jesmond]] in the 1930s, and he included Longbenton in his poem ''Hymn to the Sun''.<ref>[http://www.sclews.me.uk/m-roberts.html Myers Literary Guide: The North-East - MICHAEL (WILLIAM EDWARD) ROBERTS (1902 - 1948)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213103256/http://www.sclews.me.uk/m-roberts.html |date=2014-12-13 }}</ref>\n\n== Government agencies ==\n[[HM Revenue & Customs]] and [[Department for Work and Pensions]] share a major base on the Longbenton/[[City of Newcastle upon Tyne]] border, known as [[Benton Park View]]. The site employs around 7,500 workers and is a significant employment source in the area.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.longbentonfc.co.uk/ Longbenton F.C] The Official Website 